36 SECTION 6. IC 8-1-47 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE AS
37 A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE UPON
38 PASSAGE]:
39 Chapter 47. Low Income Customer Assistance Programs for
40 Electric Utility Service
41 Sec. 1. As used in this chapter, "electricity supplier" means a
42 person, however organized, that:
2026 IN 1002—LS 7032/DI 101

24
1 (1) provides utility service to customers; and
2 (2) is under the jurisdiction of the commission for the
3 approval of rates and charges.
4 Sec. 2. (a) As used in this chapter, "eligible program costs"
5 means costs that are associated with an electricity supplier's low
6 income customer assistance program and that:
7 (1) have been incurred, or are reasonably estimated to be
8 incurred, by the electricity supplier in administering the low
9 income customer assistance program, including
10 administrative activities involving:
11 (A) customer eligibility verification;
12 (B) billing services; and
13 (C) contribution management; and
14 (2) have not been and will not be recovered by the electricity
15 supplier through:
16 (A) a required allocation under section 6 of this chapter; or
17 (B) contributions of any money, services, or property that
18 have been or will be provided at no cost to the electricity
19 supplier by or through any:
20 (i) governmental agency or program; or
21 (ii) other third party, including voluntary charitable
22 contributions from nonprofit organizations or from
23 employees, customers, or shareholders of the electricity
24 supplier;
25 in support of the program.
26 (b) The term does not include lost revenues associated with an
27 electricity supplier's low income customer assistance program.
28 Sec. 3. As used in this chapter, "low income customer" refers to
29 a residential customer who is part of a household that:
30 (1) has agreed to pay for utility service from an electricity
31 supplier; and
32 (2) is eligible for and has applied for assistance from a home
33 energy assistance program administered under IC 4-4-33.
34 Sec. 4. As used in this chapter, "utility service" means electric
35 service that is provided at retail to customers.
36 Sec. 5. (a) Not later than July 1, 2026, an electricity supplier
37 shall offer a low income customer assistance program that provides
38 financial assistance to low income customers for the payment of
39 monthly bills for utility service provided by the electricity supplier.
40 A program that:
41 (1) is offered by the electricity supplier before July 1, 2026;
42 (2) provides financial assistance to low income customers for
2026 IN 1002—LS 7032/DI 101

25
1 the payment of monthly bills for utility service provided by
2 the electricity supplier;
3 (3) remains in effect on July 1, 2026; and
4 (4) includes eligibility criteria consistent with section 3(2) of
5 this chapter;
6 qualifies as a low income customer assistance program for
7 purposes of this section.
8 (b) Subject to subsection (c), an electricity supplier may
9 establish:
10 (1) per customer funding limits;
11 (2) enrollment limits; or
12 (3) other limits, caps, or restrictions;
13 applicable to the low income customer assistance program based
14 on funds available for the program from governmental agencies or
15 programs or from other third parties, including voluntary
16 charitable contributions from nonprofit organizations or from
17 employees, customers, or shareholders of the electricity supplier.
18 (c) If at any time during a calendar year:
19 (1) an electricity supplier is no longer able to offer assistance
20 to additional eligible customers under the electricity
21 supplier's low income customer assistance program as a result
22 of any limit, cap, or restriction established under subsection
23 (b); and
24 (2) the full amount allocated or to be allocated to the program
25 under section 6 of this chapter has not been allocated to low
26 income customers enrolled in the program at the time the
27 limit, cap, or restriction is reached;
28 the portion of the amount allocated or to be allocated to the
29 program under section 6 of this chapter that has not been allocated
30 to low income customers enrolled in the program at time the limit,
31 cap, or restriction is reached shall be segregated from all other
32 funds of the electricity supplier and held in trust for allocation to
33 low income customers enrolled in the electricity supplier's low
34 income customer assistance program in the following calendar
35 year.
36 Sec. 6. (a) Beginning in 2027, not later than March 1 of each
37 year, an electricity supplier shall allocate to the electricity
38 supplier's low income customer assistance program an amount
39 equal to at least fifty percent (50%) of the amount of any lost
40 revenues recovered by the electricity supplier during the most
41 recently concluded calendar year under:
42 (1) IC 8-1-8.5-9(l), in the case of an electricity supplier that is
2026 IN 1002—LS 7032/DI 101

26
1 not a public utility (as defined in IC 8-1-2-1(a)); or
2 (2) IC 8-1-8.5-10(o)(2), in the case of an electricity supplier
3 that is a public utility (as defined in IC 8-1-2-1(a));
4 as approved program costs associated with an energy efficiency
5 program offered by the electricity supplier.
6 (b) The commission shall prescribe in the rules adopted by the
7 commission under section 12 of this chapter the procedures by
8 which an electricity supplier shall:
9 (1) make; and
10 (2) report to the commission;
11 a transfer required by this section.
12 Sec. 7. (a) In each residential customer bill issued by an
13 electricity supplier after June 30, 2026, the electricity supplier
14 must include a notice that:
15 (1) informs customers that the electricity supplier offers a low
16 income customer assistance program for eligible customers;
17 and
18 (2) includes:
19 (A) a toll free telephone number; or
20 (B) a link to a web page;
21 that a customer may call or access for information on how to
22 apply for assistance under the program.
23 (b) Not later than July 1, 2026, the electricity supplier shall post
24 the information described in subsection (a)(1) and (a)(2) on the
25 electricity supplier's website. If at any time during a calendar year,
26 the electricity supplier is no longer able to offer assistance to
27 additional eligible customers under the electricity supplier's low
28 income customer assistance program as a result of any:
29 (1) per customer funding limits;
30 (2) enrollment limits; or
31 (3) other limits, caps, or restrictions;
32 established by the electricity supplier under section 5(b) of this
33 chapter, the electricity supplier shall include on its website a
34 statement notifying customers of that fact. If the electricity
35 supplier is subsequently able to enroll new eligible customers in the
36 program during that calendar year, the electricity supplier shall
37 remove the previously posted statement from its website and post
38 a new statement indicating that the program is again accepting
39 new applications for assistance.
40 Sec. 8. If a customer:
41 (1) applies for assistance under an electricity supplier's low
42 income customer assistance program; and
2026 IN 1002—LS 7032/DI 101

27
1 (2) qualifies as a low income customer under section 3(2) of
2 this chapter;
3 the electricity supplier shall enroll the customer in the program, to
4 the extent the electricity supplier is able to do so under any per
5 customer funding limits, enrollment limits, or other limits, caps, or
6 restrictions established by the electricity supplier under section
7 5(b) of this chapter and applicable at the time of the customer's
8 application.
9 Sec. 9. (a) An electricity supplier may, but is not required to,
10 petition the commission for approval to recover eligible program
11 costs. An electricity supplier may file a petition the commission
12 under this section:
13 (1) as part of a base rate case; or
14 (2) at any time as part of an independent proceeding in which
15 the electricity supplier petitions the commission to recover
16 eligible program costs on a timely basis through a periodic
17 rate adjustment mechanism.
18 (b) A petition under subsection (a)(2) for approval of a rate
19 schedule that periodically adjusts the electricity supplier's rates
20 and charges to provide for the timely recovery of eligible program
21 costs must include the following for a twelve (12) month period set
22 forth in the electricity supplier's petition:
23 (1) A description of any money, services, or property that has
24 been or will be provided at no cost to the electricity supplier
25 by or through any:
26 (A) governmental agency or program; or
27 (B) other third party, including voluntary charitable
28 contributions from nonprofit organizations or from
29 employees, customers, or shareholders of the electricity
30 supplier;
31 in support of the low income customer assistance program,
32 including the actual or estimated amount or value of the
33 money, services, or property described.
34 (2) A statement of any amounts that have been or will be
35 allocated to the electricity supplier's low income customer
36 assistance program under section 6 of this chapter.
37 (3) A breakdown of eligible program costs that have been or
38 will be incurred by the electricity supplier, including the:
39 (A) amounts; and
40 (B) purposes;
41 for which they have been or will be incurred.
42 A rate schedule proposed by an electricity supplier under this
2026 IN 1002—LS 7032/DI 101

28
1 subsection may be based in whole or in part on reasonable cost
2 forecasts over all or any part of the twelve (12) month period on
3 which the electricity supplier's petition is based, subject to the
4 commission's consideration of the electricity supplier's historical
5 forecasting accuracy. If forecasted data is used, the proposed rate
6 schedule must provide for a reconciliation mechanism to correct
7 for any variance between the forecasted eligible program costs and
8 the actual eligible program costs incurred.
9 (c) Subject to subsection (d), after reviewing an electricity
10 supplier's petition under subsection (a)(2), the commission
11 determines that:
12 (1) the electricity supplier has incurred or will incur eligible
13 program costs that are reasonable in amount;
14 (2) notwithstanding section 10 of this chapter, the effect or the
15 potential effect, in both the long and short term, of the
16 proposed rate schedule on the electric rates of
17 nonparticipating customers or other customer classes of the
18 electricity supplier will be minimal; and
19 (3) approval of the proposed rate schedule is in the public
20 interest;
21 the commission shall approve the electricity supplier's proposed
22 rate schedule under subsection (b).
23 (d) The commission may not approve a rate schedule under
24 subsection (b) that would result in an average aggregate increase
25 in an electricity supplier's total retail revenues of more than two
26 percent (2%) with respect to the twelve (12) month period on
27 which the electricity supplier's proposed rate schedule is based. If
28 an electricity supplier incurs eligible program costs in connection
29 with the electricity supplier's low income customer assistance
30 program that exceed the limit set forth in this subsection, the
31 electricity supplier may seek to recover those eligible program
32 costs for recovery in the electricity supplier's next base rate case.
33 Sec. 10. A low income customer assistance program offered
34 under this chapter that affects rates and charges for service is not
35 discriminatory for purposes of this chapter or any other law
36 regulating rates and charges for service.
37 Sec. 11. (a) Beginning in 2027, the commission shall include in
38 the annual report that the commission is required to submit under
39 IC 8-1-1-14 before October 1 of each year the following
40 information for each electricity supplier with respect to the most
41 recently concluded state fiscal year:
42 (1) The number of low income customers enrolled in the
2026 IN 1002—LS 7032/DI 101

29
1 electricity supplier's low income customer assistance program
2 at the beginning and end of the state fiscal year.
3 (2) The total amount of assistance provided to low income
4 customers under the electricity supplier's program.
5 (3) The median amount of assistance provided to each
6 customer under the electricity supplier's program.
7 (4) Subject to subsection (c), an identification of the sources
8 and amounts of any money, services, or property contributed
9 to the electricity supplier's program by or through:
10 (A) governmental agencies or programs; or
11 (B) other third parties, including voluntary charitable
12 contributions from nonprofit organizations or from
13 employees, customers, or shareholders of the electricity
14 supplier.
15 (5) An identification of the amounts of any:
16 (A) per customer funding limits;
17 (B) enrollment limits; or
18 (C) other limits, caps, or restrictions;
19 established by the electricity supplier under section 5(b) of
20 this chapter, along with information as to whether and when
21 any such limits, caps, or restrictions were reached or applied
22 during the state fiscal year.
23 (b) Subject to subsection (c), an electricity supplier shall provide
24 the commission, at the time and in the manner prescribed by the
25 commission, any information required under subsection (a) to be
26 included in the commission's annual report.
27 (c) Upon request by an electricity supplier, the commission shall
28 determine whether any information and related materials
29 described in subsection (a):
30 (1) are confidential under IC 5-14-3-4;
31 (2) are exempt from public access and disclosure by Indiana
32 law; and
33 (3) must be treated as confidential and protected from public
34 access and disclosure by the commission.
35 In addition, an electricity supplier is not required to name
36 individual third party donors under subsection (a)(4) and may
37 instead report the types of third party organizations and
38 individuals that contributed to the electricity supplier's program
39 and the amounts contributed by each type.
40 Sec. 12. The commission shall adopt rules under IC 4-22-2 to
41 implement this chapter.
42 SECTION 7. [EFFECTIVE UPON PASSAGE] (a) As used in this
2026 IN 1002—LS 7032/DI 101

30
1 SECTION, "commission" refers to the Indiana utility regulatory
2 commission created by IC 8-1-1-2.
3 (b) Not later than May 1, 2026, the commission shall amend the
4 following rules of the commission as necessary to conform the rules
5 with IC 8-1-2-121, as amended by this act:
6 (1) 170 IAC 4.
7 (2) 170 IAC 5.
8 (3) Any other rule that:
9 (A) has been adopted by the commission; and
10 (B) is inconsistent with IC 8-1-2-121, as amended by this
11 act.
12 (c) This SECTION expires January 1, 2027.
13 SECTION 8. [EFFECTIVE UPON PASSAGE] (a) Before January
14 1, 2027, the commission shall amend 170 IAC 4-1-23 as necessary
15 to conform 170 IAC 4-1-23 to the requirements of IC 8-1-46, as
16 added by this act.
17 (b) This SECTION expires January 2, 2027.
18 SECTION 9. An emergency is declared for this act.
